A unique old chapel on Margit-sziget (Margaret Island) in the heart of Budapest. The island itself is an awesome place where nature and man can meet leaving behind the buzz of the city. A lot of people go there all the year to spend a good time enjoying nature and each other's company.

A roman style church built centuries ago and destroyed throughly during ottoman times, its bell found in 1920 among the roots of a chestnut tree and ıt has been built stone by stone again in 1940. The most overwhelmingly big basilica I have seen, truly a masterpiece of scale and detail. The size of the building is hard to comprehend and the level of craftsmanship is deeply impressive. I visited at night which only added to the dramatic nature of the building.

Very beautiful historical building in Hungary. Most of the free tour starts here. 
The height of the church is 96 meters, 96 is a unique and special number to Hungarians. The Parliament building is also 96 meters. There is a law in Hungary saying all the buildings at the Pest side of Budapest cannot be taller than 96 meters because no one can be above God and government. 
The entrance of the church is free, but feel free to donate money to the church, or you can also buy a small coin token at the vending machine there. 
The interior of the church is also very beautiful. If you have time, please join the free tour, it is much more informative and the tour guides are very friendly and helpful. Of course, they earn by tips, feel free to give based on what you think the tour is worth. It is totally fantastic.

A lot of the tours around Budapest start here and you can even go in and climb to the top for an unbelievable veiw of the whole city, it costs though. Grab a drink at one of the delightful bars just outside and sit at one of the outside seating areas and soak in the culture and people watch.

Really nice place to visit. From the top of the church you have panoramic views of the whole city of Budapest and also it overlooks the square in front of the church. Great spot for wonderful city views and for taking photos. Just note that you have to buy a ticket in order to get access.

The Buda Castle is an amazing place to visit. It's a walking distance from the Fisherman's Bastion which is also a fabulous sight to behold. You can get a great view/snap shot of the city including the Parliament building, the Danube chain bridge and the Budapest eye. I and my friends had a great time sight seeing and taking cool pictures here.

Great place with great views. This is a must visit if you are in Budapest. The view of the bridges along with the parliament building and the city skyline is just majestic. Especially during dusk, one can literally experience the beauty with the lights being lit up

You’ll find mostly produce, meats, baked goods, and candy on the ground floor, while the upper floor is home to restaurants and souvenir shops. It has a lot of traditional places to eat, so be sure to walk around and explore first.

A Kőbányai Református Egyházközség Temploma a Gergely utca-Ihász utca sarkán található, nagy méretű, kiváló állapotban lévő, impozáns épület. Udvarán márványtáblán az utcáról is jól látható módon el van helyezve a tízparancsolat. A Kőbányai Református gyülekezet templomában vasárnaponként nyolc és tíz órai kezdettel Istentiszteletet, délután öt órakor orgonás vesperás Istentiszteletet tart a helyi lelkész, olykor a felesége és egy fiatal lelkésznő. Igehirdetéseik, magyarázataik érthető módon, olykor humoros, az életből vett tapasztalattal fűszerezve kerülnek előadásra a megjelent hívők részére. Vasárnap délelöttönként a templom megtellik szinte teljesen hívő református emberekkel, akik között sok a fiatal, még gyermek is szép számmal. A templom, hála a lelkésznek kívül belül gondozott, felújíott, mindig tiszta és ápolt, még a kertje és utcarésze is. A templom kívülről belülről az egyik legszebben kivitelezett Református épület. Hatalmas saját orgonával rendelkezik, melyet minden alkalommal gondos, precíz, szakértő kezek szólaltatnak meg. Hálás vagyok Istennek, hogy ide járhatok tisztelni Őt vasárnaponként akár kétszer is, ha épp kedvem úgy tartja.
Többször voltam itt hiteles, érvényes istentiszteleten. Az épület pedig elképesztő!

The biggest cemetery in Hungary, truly massive. We visited some relatives here and you drive around by car as it's so big. Some of the older plots at the back are on dirt tracks, some very overgrown, barely passable by a single car with branches scraping the sides. The newer grave markers are in good condition and obviously cared for. It's sad to see some of the older plots at the back sections are completely overgrown with large trees and plants growing through and over headstones. It's more like a dense forest with the occasional falling over headstones visible. Very creepy. The front part of the cemetery has maps to guide you to the particular site you are looking for. I suggest you take a photo as it is quite easy to get lost, especially as quite a few of the extensive road network is one way streets. There is an Italian section of war Graves from the second world war not far from the main entrance which is quite interesting.

The most overwhelmingly big basilica I have seen, truly a masterpiece of scale and detail. The size of the building is hard to comprehend and the level of craftsmanship is deeply impressive. I visited at night which only added to the dramatic nature of the building.

Very beautiful historical building in Hungary. Most of the free tour starts here. 
The height of the church is 96 meters, 96 is a unique and special number to Hungarians. The Parliament building is also 96 meters. There is a law in Hungary saying all the buildings at the Pest side of Budapest cannot be taller than 96 meters because no one can be above God and government. 
The entrance of the church is free, but feel free to donate money to the church, or you can also buy a small coin token at the vending machine there. 
The interior of the church is also very beautiful. If you have time, please join the free tour, it is much more informative and the tour guides are very friendly and helpful. Of course, they earn by tips, feel free to give based on what you think the tour is worth. It is totally fantastic.

Very beautiful building right in the centre of a lovely little square with a few bars restaurants and an ice cream shop. A lot of the tours around Budapest start here and you can even go in and climb to the top for an unbelievable veiw of the whole city, it costs though. Grab a drink at one of the delightful bars just outside and sit at one of the outside seating areas and soak in the culture and people watch.

Really nice place to visit. From the top of the church you have panoramic views of the whole city of Budapest and also it overlooks the square in front of the church. Great spot for wonderful city views and for taking photos. Just note that you have to buy a ticket in order to get access.
You need to spend time to admire the beauty of this building. I was lucky to hear some great music being played by a lady inside. Really intricate architecture. Loved it!

Slovak Technical Museum – Museum of Transport – documents the development of railway and road transport of Slovakia. Cars with or without engine produced before the World War II. Bicycles, personal vehicles and lorries from the interwar period. Vehicles from the 60s and 70s of the 20th century. All this plus some temporary exhibitions will bring you closer to understand how Slovak transportation has changed in time. The exposures are situated in former stores, built in the characteristic industrial style of the early 20th century. You will travel in time thanks to this visit!

A good place to visit,  possibly on rainy days. The market hall is vast. The ground floor and lower ground floor are food related. There are a variety of stalls some of which offer free tasting of meat products. On the upper floor is Ann area which caters for clothing and soft goods. Don't miss the food court which offers a variety of tasty food cooked fresh.

Built in 1897, this is the oldest and largest indoor market in the country, a bit southwest of the Jewish Quarter. You’ll find mostly produce, meats, baked goods, and candy on the ground floor, while the upper floor is home to restaurants and souvenir shops. It has a lot of traditional places to eat, so be sure to walk around and explore first.

Very huge and interesting market. Meat, fruits, vegetables and other ingredients are on the ground floor. Souvenirs, clothes and take away food is on the top floor. You can find a fish market and an Aldi supermarket in the basement. Good point to buy traditional folk dress accessories.

Most beautiful old style market building with many stores. Fresh food downstairs with typical Hungarian dishes - Paprika based! Great for souvenirs upstairs if a little tacky and over-priced. Always very busy but 100% worth seeing.

Szép étterem.

Professzionális, udvarias kiszolgálás, rendezett környezet, hangulatos atmoszféra, piros-fehér kockás békebeli abroszok az asztalokon, ízletesen elkészített fogások (mi csak a bolgár specialitásokból rendeltünk). Külön kiemelném a mellékhelyiség patyolattisztaságát. Egyetlen hiányosságként a bolgár italkinálat hiányát nevezném meg.

Bolgár ételspecialitásokat is kínáló étterem. Kellemes, otthonos, piros-fehér kockás abroszos asztalokkal teli terasza van. Külön jó, hogy a mini játszótéren a gyerekek tudnak mozogni, amíg a felnőttek esznek és ejtőznek. A bográcsgulyás és a somlói nagyon finom volt, a húsleves kicsit állottnak tűnt, a grillezett jércemell hasábburgonyája szikkadt volt, de lehet, hogy magasak voltak az elvárások. Az ételek ára kifejezetten kedvező, mondhatni olcsó a hely. Ami miatt csak három csillag az értékelés, hogy a pincér elképesztően lassú volt, egy vendég el is ment az étteremből, mivel a pincér 15 perc után sem jelent meg az asztalánál. A mosdóba menet a takarító megszólt minket, hogy miért járkáljuk össze a padlót, amikor ő most mosott fel. Ez meglehetősen abszurd volt.
Autentikus bolgár ételek, egyedi hangulat.

I really feel like you could come here 2 or 3 times and still learn or see something new here. Absolutely beautiful in hundreds of ways, witnessing this building and all its treasures firsthand is something spectacular. Pictures don't do it justice.

Anything to do with Amsterdam is already good enough for me. Add to that a chance to take in the Royal Palace, the cherry has been placed on my tourism cake. 

Taking a walking tour was well worth it. We learned so much from our guide, it truly made the experience memorable.

If you have the time, why not do it? The architecture that surrounds the area alone, is well worth it.

First of all, if you're into interesting buildings, you can never go wrong with palaces. This type of buildings are always the place of many interesting stories. This city hall turned palace during the reign of Napoleon is no different. Large halls full of exquisite art and the most expensive furniture give you a peek at how it is to be a dignitary in the Netherlands. The excellent audio tour (with a special version for kids) in a dozen languages that allows you to wander through the halls in your own tempo makes it a five star to visit. No rush, just interesting history.

It’s amazing that you’re able to walk in and explore the actual Royal Palace! There’s a wide range of different rooms - all with unique snippets of history attached. Joy for the whole family - would definitely recommend visiting it if you’re in Amsterdam.

Unlike many other sightseeing places, this one is very kid- and English-friendly. Kids get their own audio guide and a little necklace to fill out to keep them interested. For adults there are various language available - including English.
For me, this is the best museum in Europe. So many fantastic works of art.
Don't waste your time. The gallery is almost empty. Go to the national museum.
Short and sweet narrative of Bangkok fine arts.
Great exhibition. Especially, Marsis great paintings.
Definitely worth a visit! Intriguing artwork, and I think I literally spent hours there.

A little off the beaten track but worth the visit. Good combination of everything from tanks to history and aircraft. As you enter the main building you can see cannons and guns from the earlier times and on your right more modern equipment. Main building gives the early years which is impressive, sometimes with a English translation which makes things easier. The heating was on at a very toasty 24 deg a little warm this time of year. In the back of the building there is a courtyard full of varying equipment which sadly is decaying over time. There are three other buildings one on transport at the back which was locked at the time. One on aviation, and another on arms. Very impressive. Overall worth a visit for anyone with a military interest.

The museum is OK, reasonable amount of exhibits and plenty of old military vehicles in the courtyard. What lets it down are the lack of explanations relating to exhibits or anything else. No map provided to help patrons find particular exhibits/areas of interest, staff not unfriendly, nor enthusiastic or overly helpful. One certainly didn't meet anyone who had any passion for sharing history with patrons which has been commonplace at nearly every other museum one has visited in my lifetime. In comparison to other museums it's pretty poor but if you have time to kill and are in the area it's worth a visit, I wouldn't advise anyone to go out of their way to visit unless you are a huge fan of real life tanks and other military vehicles as seeing them up close in the flesh is really the only selling point of the place.

Great museum, but be aware there are not a lot of explanations inside. The museum assumes a good knowledge of the Romanian history.  The decaying military vehicles in the courtyard are very interesting to explore.

Great place to visit in Bucharest, hosting an impressive collection of objects from the Romanian military history. It covers all the historical times from the bronze age to contemporary present day. Make sure you also go to the courtyard behind the main building where for real size military equipments like tanks, guns, trucks & even aircrafts. 

As well, there are 3 other pavilions situated in the back of the main building that host collections of military transport vehicles & chariots, military uniforms & weapons. 

Prices range from 5 lei (children & students) to 20 lei (adults). Just make sure you have cash with you because you can't pay by card at the entrance.

A great museum where you can learn a lot about Romania's history from a military point of view. It features from crude stone tools to rockets used until the 1990's. Small scale fortification and castle models. A lot of maps and uniforms. And from small artillery guns that could be towed by horses to train fixed heavy artillery guns. Tanks, planes, armoured carriers old and relatively new.
There is a main museum, in another building a level for guns and a level for uniforms, another building for aviation related stuff and also one building.(which was closed) with parachutes and related material.

Nice to go up and see the city from the top. We have s 360 degree view from the top. You can climb the steps or there is a lift that we discovered on the way down, only takes 4 people each way, so prepare to wait in line. The views from the top were very nice.

The most overwhelmingly big basilica I have seen, truly a masterpiece of scale and detail. The size of the building is hard to comprehend and the level of craftsmanship is deeply impressive. I visited at night which only added to the dramatic nature of the building.

Very beautiful historical building in Hungary. Most of the free tour starts here. 
The height of the church is 96 meters, 96 is a unique and special number to Hungarians. The Parliament building is also 96 meters. There is a law in Hungary saying all the buildings at the Pest side of Budapest cannot be taller than 96 meters because no one can be above God and government. 
The entrance of the church is free, but feel free to donate money to the church, or you can also buy a small coin token at the vending machine there. 
The interior of the church is also very beautiful. If you have time, please join the free tour, it is much more informative and the tour guides are very friendly and helpful. Of course, they earn by tips, feel free to give based on what you think the tour is worth. It is totally fantastic.

Very beautiful building right in the centre of a lovely little square with a few bars restaurants and an ice cream shop. A lot of the tours around Budapest start here and you can even go in and climb to the top for an unbelievable veiw of the whole city, it costs though. Grab a drink at one of the delightful bars just outside and sit at one of the outside seating areas and soak in the culture and people watch.

Really nice place to visit. From the top of the church you have panoramic views of the whole city of Budapest and also it overlooks the square in front of the church. Great spot for wonderful city views and for taking photos. Just note that you have to buy a ticket in order to get access.

Loved it. 
Alot of excellent stores and shopping at Macy's was Great

This historic building is very important for the city of Chicago. This building is the only one, that survived Chicago's great fire in 1871. Now surrounded with chic shopping district and Magnificent Mile, it serves like a tourist destination.
Beautiful building where you can find art and learn about the city.

Really pretty we stayed near the tower for a birthday weekend in my home town chicago. I was hoping to see it at night but chicago weathee had other plans. Some issues trash on the ground and people trying to sell "school candy".
Interesting view over Chicago. One of the important must see attractions in Chicago.

Beautiful rose garden, well maintained. Do come on weekends. Its located in sector 15. Space for car parking also available. You can enjoy coconut water, various flavor of ice creams, lemon soda. Best time to visit is in evening as it glows various colour full lights there. Lot of fountains with ample sitting space. Best for jogging yoga exercise, whatever you love to do.

The Rose Garden as the name suggest has different varieties of roses white , red, Yellow, orange,pink with a specific scientific name written...
The sizes of roses are also very Big.
The park is large and spread over 30 acres..
The garden is well maintained with good grass..
The trees also beautiful..
It also has a fountain..

Good to spend time here
Moreover eating facilities and washrooms are also available..
A Nala passes in between the park and has bridge to cross over it..

My mom used to come here when she lived in Chandigarh for a while. When I visited, it was nice. However, i noticed that the water (lake) was drained. It did not look very aesthetic. Wish they were fixing it at a different time. The flowers look very beautiful. If you are in Chandigarh, I recommend visiting this garden. It is also a great place for studying or reading (or relaxing in general). I just want to put out a request for people to not damage the flowers and plants. If you are taking photos, please be aware of your surroundings. This is a beautiful place, and we should keep it this way.

Visited during summer vacations and hardly found any rose. Summer definitely not the right time to visit the garden. There is not much greenery also to sit during summer. Recommended for other seasons. Kids did not enjoy much and all we could see was little squirrel 🐿 at entrance. Must be much better place during season other than summer.

Opened in 1967, this place has been one of the scenic beauty types place where you can visit anytime for nice views. The garden is well managed by the managing body. Also if you are one who is very fond of roses and would like to take a look at different varieties of roses, then this is the place for you. Also during the time of valentine's week, there is a rose festival organised here. So visit this place during this time and you will definitely worth it. For the rest of the year, this place is chic and quiet. So a good place for finding peaceful environment for a short time in a day or so
